</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walckenaer" baseAuthorityYear="1837" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hogna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hogna maderiana" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Hogna maderiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was assessed according to the IUCN Red List criteria as 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. schmitzi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmitzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. schmitzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048645A58061027.en" author="Cardoso, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" refId="B18" refString="Cardoso, P, Crespo, LC, Silva, I, Borges, P, Boieiro, M, 2018d. Hogna schmitzi. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2018. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048645A58061027.en" title="Hogna schmitzi. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2018." url="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048645A58061027.en" year="2018 d">Cardoso et al. 2018d</bibRefCitation>
), with the status of Least Concern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
As mentioned above (see remarks on 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. blackwalli" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blackwalli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. blackwalli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the large specimens with striking orange coloration in legs from Porto Santo island and its neighbouring islet 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ilhéu">Ilheu</normalizedToken>
de Ferro were known to pioneer arachnologists. The original, somewhat obscure, description by Walckenaer described a 2.5 cm spider (&quot;1 pouce&quot;) with reddish brown legs (&quot;Pattes rouges, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="lavées">lavees</normalizedToken>
de brun en dessus (
<normalizedToken originalValue="…)”">...)&quot;</normalizedToken>
), from the island of Madeira (&quot;Ile de 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Madère”">Madere&quot;</normalizedToken>
). After this, Blackwall was the first to provide a clear description of this taxon, while at the same time stating that it was collected in the island of Porto Santo, not Madeira. Subsequent authors reported additional material from either Porto Santo or 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ilhéu">Ilheu</normalizedToken>
de Ferro (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936308681494" author="Johnson, J" journalOrPublisher="Annals and Magazine of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" pagination="152 - 155" refId="B40" refString="Johnson, J, 1863. Description of a new species of Lycosa living in the island of Madeira; with some remarks on the Lycosa tarentuloides maderiana Walckenaer. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 12: 152 - 155, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936308681494" title="Description of a new species of Lycosa living in the island of Madeira; with some remarks on the Lycosa tarentuloides maderiana Walckenaer." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222936308681494" volume="12" year="1863">Johnson 1863</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kulczynski, W" journalOrPublisher="Rozprawy i Sprawozdania z Posiedzen Wydzialu Matematyczno Przyrodniczego Akademji Umiejetnosci, Krakow" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" pagination="319 - 461" refId="B44" refString="Kulczynski, W, 1899. Arachnoidea opera Rev. E. Schmitz collecta in insulis Maderianis et in insulis Selvages dictis. Rozprawy i Sprawozdania z Posiedzen Wydzialu Matematyczno Przyrodniczego Akademji Umiejetnosci, Krakow 36: 319 - 461" title="Arachnoidea opera Rev. E. Schmitz collecta in insulis Maderianis et in insulis Selvages dictis." volume="36" year="1899">Kulczynski 1899</bibRefCitation>
). Wunderlich considered 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. blackwalli" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blackwalli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. blackwalli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a junior synonymy of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. maderiana" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. maderiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the wrong assumption that previous authors repeatedly misidentified 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. maderiana" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. maderiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Porto Santo, assigning 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. maderiana" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maderiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. maderiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the large species with annulated legs from Madeira island. Following synonymy, Wunderlich himself named the large species from Porto Santo as 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. schmitzi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmitzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. schmitzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. As a matter of fact, the only indication of the presence of a large spider with reddish leg coloration in Madeira island is 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Walckenaer’s">Walckenaer's</normalizedToken>
original description. Unfortunately, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Walckenaer’s">Walckenaer's</normalizedToken>
type seems to be lost. However, Simon most likely examined it because he stated that &quot; 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. maderiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" rank="species" species="maderiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">L. maderiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Walck. est, en grande partie, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="revêtu">revetu</normalizedToken>
, en dessus, de pubescence courte 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’un">d'un</normalizedToken>
beau rouge orange.&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Simon, E" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" refId="B67" refString="Simon, E, 1898. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Deuxieme edition, tome second. Roret (Ed.), Paris, 193-380." title="Histoire naturelle des araignees. Deuxieme edition, tome second. Roret (Ed.), Paris, 193 - 380." year="1898">Simon 1898</bibRefCitation>
: 332). The two large species are easy to distinguish, the only misidentification between them being made by Thorell, who identified 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. blackwalli" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blackwalli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. blackwalli</emphasis>
